  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2><p>Common questions about international credit cards</p></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Do I need to enable international transactions on my card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, most Indian banks disable international transactions by default for security. You need to enable it through your banking app, net banking, or by calling customer service. Banks typically let you set a per-transaction and daily international spending limit. Some banks allow temporary enablement for specific date ranges (ideal for trips). You can also enable/disable international usage instantly through apps like HDFC PayZapp, ICICI iMobile, or Axis Mobile. Always disable international transactions when not needed for added security.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What's the RBI LRS limit for credit card international spending?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Under RBI's Liberalised Remittance Scheme (LRS), Indian residents can remit up to USD 250,000 per financial year (April-March) for permissible transactions including travel, education, medical treatment, and international purchases. Credit card transactions abroad count toward this limit. From October 2023, a Tax Collected at Source (TCS) of 20% applies on international credit card spending exceeding ₹7 lakh per year (this TCS is adjustable against your income tax). Education and medical payments have lower TCS rates of 0.5% and 5% respectively.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Which card network is best for international use — Visa or Mastercard?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Both Visa and Mastercard have similar global acceptance at 80 million+ merchants worldwide. The difference lies in specific regions and programs: Visa has slightly better acceptance in the Americas, while Mastercard is marginally more accepted in Europe. Both offer similar lounge programs and travel insurance. The choice between them should be based on the specific card's benefits rather than the network. For maximum coverage, having one card from each network is ideal. Note that Diners Club and Amex have more limited international acceptance compared to Visa and Mastercard.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What happens if my international card is lost abroad?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">If your card is lost or stolen while abroad: (1) Immediately block it through your banking app or by calling the bank's 24/7 international helpline (save this number before travelling), (2) Report the loss to local police and get a copy of the FIR, (3) Request an emergency card replacement — premium cards deliver a temporary replacement within 48-72 hours to your hotel, (4) Meanwhile, use contactless payments via phone if you had added the card to Google Pay or Apple Pay. Your zero-liability protection ensures you're not charged for any fraudulent transactions made after the loss.</div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can students studying abroad get an international credit card?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, students have several options: (1) Add-on card — get an add-on international card linked to a parent's primary card, (2) Secured card — place an FD and get a secured international card in your own name, (3) Student-specific cards — some banks offer international cards designed for students with a parent as co-applicant, (4) Prepaid forex cards — while not credit cards, these offer zero forex markup and are easy to get. For students, the IDFC First WOW card (lifetime free, zero forex) or a secured card from ICICI/Kotak are excellent options to start building credit while studying abroad.</div></div></div>
    </div>
